{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507475"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:53:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:53:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2628"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2628"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.1,0.01,0.06,0.57]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2628"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102165"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2628"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2628"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84623"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2939"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2940"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35630"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102165"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for review of her International Normalised Ratio (INR). She reports feeling well and has been trying to live a healthier lifestyle with regular swimming and increased salad consumption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has a mechanical aortic valve inserted five years ago and takes warfarin. She has hypertension managed with perindopril, the dose of which was increased at her General Practice appointment last week. She is also currently taking a course of oral fluconazole involving every other day treatment for recurrent candidate vulvovaginitis, and feels her symptoms have improved since she started this a week ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her INR today is 5.0 (2.5-3.5). Previous INR results have been between 2.0-2.5.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of her raised INR?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased spinach intake","Increased perindopril dose","Chlorine exposure from swimming","Missed warfarin doses","Fluconazole treatment"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a significantly elevated INR likely due to a drug interaction. \u003Cstrong\u003EFluconazole\u003C/strong\u003E inhibits cytochrome P450 enzymes responsible for warfarin metabolism, leading to reduced warfarin clearance and increased anticoagulant effect. This is a common and clinically significant interaction that requires careful monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased spinach intake\u003C/strong\u003E would actually lower the INR as vitamin K antagonises warfarin\u0027s effect. Dietary consistency is important for patients on warfarin, but increased consumption of vitamin K-rich foods would reduce, not increase, the INR.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased perindopril dose\u003C/strong\u003E would not affect the INR as angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors do not interact significantly with warfarin metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChlorine exposure from swimming\u003C/strong\u003E has no effect on warfarin metabolism or INR levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMissed warfarin doses\u003C/strong\u003E would result in a decreased, not increased, INR as there would be less anticoagulant effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMechanical heart valves require higher target INR ranges (typically 2.5-3.5) than other indications for warfarin due to their higher thrombotic risk. This makes drug interactions particularly concerning as even small changes in warfarin metabolism can lead to clinically significant changes in anticoagulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fluconazole inhibits warfarin metabolism through CYP450, leading to increased INR.","Increased dietary vitamin K (e.g. leafy greens) reduces INR by antagonising warfarin\u0027s effect.","Mechanical heart valves require higher target INR ranges (2.5-3.5) than other indications."],"references":["Wasmann R, Bruggemann R, 2019. A stitch in time saves nine. The Lancet. Vol 393, Issue 10184, Pg 1936. Access at: https://doi.org/10.1016/S0140-6736(19)30217-X","Thompson G, Husney A, 2020. Warfarin and Vitamin K. University of Michigan Medicine. Access at: https://www.uofmhealth.org/health-library/abo1632.","Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Warfarin (Internet). AMH. 2021. Access at: https://amhonline-amh-net-au.proxy.library.adelaide.edu.au/chapters/blood-electrolytes/anticoagulants/other-anticoagulants/warfarin.","Hersh, Elliot. (2017). Fluconazole-Warfarin Interaction: A case report with deadly consequences. Australasian Medical Journal. 10. 10.21767/AMJ.2017.3049.","Kido K, Ball J. Optimal Intensity of Warfarin Therapy in Patients With Mechanical Aortic Valves. J Pharm Pract. 2019 Feb;32(1):93-98. doi: 10.1177/0897190017734765. Epub 2017 Oct 5. PMID: 28982306."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84623"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2628"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84623"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-09T12:08:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-0